2 HOUSE BILL 238
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Public Safety
4 3–113.
5 (a) The investigating unit of a law enforcement agency shall immediately review
6 a complaint by a member of the public alleging police officer misconduct.
7 (b) An administrative charging committee shall review and make a determination
8 or ask for further review within 30 days after completion of the investigating unit’s review.
9 (c) [The] EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (E) OF THIS SECTION, FOR
10 AN INCIDENT INVOLVING A MEMBER OF THE PUBLIC AND A POLICE OFFICER, THE
11 process of review by the investigating unit through disposition by the administrative
12 charging committee shall be completed within 1 year and 1 day after the [filing of a
13 complaint by a citizen] DATE THAT THE APPROPRIATE OFFICIAL EMPLOYED BY THE
14 LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY BECAME AWARE OF THE INCIDENT.
15 (D) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (E) OF THIS SECTION, A LAW
16 ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL FILE ANY ADMINISTRATIVE CHARGES ARISING OUT
17 OF AN INVESTIGATION OF ALLEGED POLICE OFFICER MISCONDUCT THAT IS NOT
18 REQUIRED TO BE REVIEWED BY AN ADMINISTRATIVE CHARGING COMMITTEE
19 WITHIN 1 YEAR AND 1 DAY AFTER THE DATE THAT THE APPROPRIATE OFFICIAL
20 EMPLOYED BY THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY BECAME AWARE OF THE INCIDENT
21 THAT LED TO THE INVESTIGATION.
22 (E) IF ALLEGED POLICE OFFICER MISCONDUCT IS RELATED TO ACTIVITY
23 THAT REASONABLY APPEARS TO BE THE SUBJECT OF A CRIMINAL INVESTIGATION,
24 AN ADMINISTRATIVE CHARGING COMMITTEE OR LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY
25 SHALL FILE ANY ADMINISTRATIVE CHARGES WITHIN 1 YEAR AND 1 DAY AFTER THE
26 DATE OF:
27 (1) THE INVESTIGATING LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY’S
28 DETERMINATION THAT THE MATTER IS NOT RELATED TO CRIMINAL ACTIVITY;
29 (2) THE FINAL DISPOSITION OF ALL RELATED CRIMINAL CHARGES;
30 OR
31 (3) THE ADMINISTRATIVE CHARGING COMMITTEE’S OR LAW
32 ENFORCEMENT AGENCY’S RECEIPT OF NOTICE THAT THE APPROPRIATE
33 PROSECUTORIAL AUTHORITY DECLINED TO FILE CRIMINAL CHARGES.

